<br>
Most guilds, as I understand it, rely totally on the guild leader, usually in consultation with officers, to decide who gets the goodies.  The problem being, of course, no matter how hard they try, soon or later they get accused of favouritism and patronage of a chosen few.<br>
<br>
Eventually a disgruntled cabal forms, harsh words are said, and BANG, half your guild resigns and goes and forms a new guild, leaving acrimony and flame-wars in their wake.<br>
<br>
In CE, you get a point for every raid and/or boss mob taken down where you are in attendance.  Loot is allocated a point value of 1, 5, 10, 15, or 20.  If you want the loot, you spend your loot points to get it.  If two or more people want the same loot, whoever has the highest number of points stored up automatically wins the item.<br>
<br>
Result?  If you attend more raids, you build up more loot points, you get more loot.  If you attend less raids, you get less loot.  Best of all, everyone know how many points people have, and they know that when someone gets loot, its because they earnt it.  No patronage, no favouritism, no guild politics.<br>
<br>
I understand MF operate something similar, only there are no fixed-point values on loot items.  When loot drops, you bid for it with your points, and the person who makes the highest bid wins the item.<br>
<br>
Now I know this has a high administrative overhead.  You need to record  who attended what raids so people get their points.  You need to maintain a central list of people’s point counts.  <br>
<br>
However, surely it’s worth it if it can stop all the guild implosions over loot?<br>
<br>
I'm curious to hear how other guilds manage to avoid falling out over loot?<br>
<br>
Ysall the Kind<br>
60 Ench <br>
Proud Recruitment Officer of Crimson Eternity<br>
