<br>
I've argued for and against point systems.  I believe that people that show up more should get referrential treatment, but at the same time, keeping up with points is a pain.  I really don't think there is a perfect method of loot distribution.  Maybe if it wasn't such a big deal could it be fairly distributed without someone feeling shorted. <p>"I will take love wherever I find it and offer it to everyone who will take it, seek knowledge from those wiser, and teach those who wish to learn from me" - Duane Allman</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ubulvyne.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bulvyne</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 294<br> <font color=#E9D756>(8/2/02 4:53:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10267.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fair Ways to Distribute Guild Loot</span><hr size=1> Points systems are a complicated, time-consuming matter. Just creating the system can be quite an effort, but if your guild is serious about high-end stuff and the fair distribution of that stuff, I do not believe there to be a fairer system.<br>
<br>
I've been in guilds with just about every loot system there is. But for every allocation/random type system, there's always holes in them big enough to stick a golem through. <br>
<br>
Having been using a points system in MF darned near since we created the guild, I am convinced that it is about as fair as it gets. Yes, there ARE still ways to &quot;bend&quot; the system, but not nearly as much as with other systems.<br>
<br>
Many of the &quot;uber&quot; guilds on other servers also have custom points-based systems. <br>
<br>
With an officer &quot;allocation&quot; system, the chance for favortism is always there, and eventually, as Ysall said, the officers get accused of it, and people are unhappy. I was in a certain guild whose officers actually allocated loot to their own camped twinks rather than to people playing their mains who were present for the loot drop.<br>
<br>
With a random system, the &quot;randomness&quot; can be a sore-spot... nothing like watching a first-drop for a guild go to someone who happened to be present for the drop, who only plays once every 3 months. OR, nothing like watching player_X win his third straight item due to the &quot;luck&quot; of the random. <br>
<br>
The bottom-line, though, is that no single system is &quot;perfect&quot;. A guild has to talk amongst themselves and decide which system THEY think is perfect. Some guilds have used allocation schemes and are completely happy with that. <br>
<br>
But to answer your question: A random-sytem is the easiest to run. Everyone who is interested sends a tell to a person doing the random, the die is rolled, tada!  The officer-allocation is a little tougher only because most officers will actually try to make people happy, knowing in advance that someone will usually always be unhappy about a distribution decision. The Points system, tho, is the most difficult simply because points must be tracked, someone who is trusted must track them (Hooray Tuan!), and all of this can be an administrative nightmare.<br>
<br>
To each his own! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
