<br>
It doesnt really matter what system you use as long as you stick to it. If you use officer allocation, the officers know they have to be careful or alienate guildmembers. If you use points, make sure the rules on earning and spending are clear.<br>
<br>
Officer Allocation is better for promoting a stronger guild...Officers can outfit those who would benefit the guild more like the main tank...but, alot of people have trouble seeing that with a better equiped main tank they will be more successful as a guild.<br>
<br>
Point systems allow everyone to feel they have a chance at something. They definately favor those who participate more, but a guild that needs a loot system is probably trying to promote participation. Whether you use fixed points or a bidding system is a personal choice. They both have advantages and disadvantages.<br>
<br>
The bottom line is that no loot system is 100% fair. Someone will always complain because the world is full of whiners who will blame the system. As long as the rules are clear and concrete, you can point the rules board and say, 'look, you know how it is and chose to live with it by staying in the guild so shut up.'<br>
<br>
If you somehow develop a loot system that is incredibly unfair, like, say, Guild leader and officers get ALL the loot until we dont want any more, then we will let you guys random for it, don't worry, you won't have any guildmembers whining.<br>
